WEBVTT

00:11.234 --> 00:18.745
Well, it's in times like these times of confusion and fear where we have to look to God's word for direction and peace.

00:19.466 --> 00:35.730
So if you've got your Bible, grab it and open it up to Luke chapter 10, where we're going to be reading the parable of the Good Samaritan, looking for direction from God's word for us knowing how to follow Jesus in the midst of this global pandemic.

00:36.098 --> 00:44.488
We're starting this new series in our home gatherings where we're talking about faith, hope and love, shaping the way that we follow Christ in this time.

00:44.648 --> 00:50.955
So I am going to be starting with love in 1 Corinthians 13 when it talks about faith, hope and love.

00:50.975 --> 00:52.657
It says, and the greatest of these is love.

00:53.097 --> 00:57.803
So we'll start there and then we'll be talking about hope and faith in the weeks to come.

00:58.423 --> 01:04.210
So I'll read Luke chapter 10 verses 25 through 37.

01:04.354 --> 01:06.397
And then I'll open our time in the Word with a prayer.

01:06.457 --> 01:07.058
Okay.

01:07.078 --> 01:10.382
This is Luke chapter 10, starting in verse 25.

01:11.724 --> 01:19.014
And behold, a lawyer stood up to put him to the test saying, teacher, what shall I do to inherit eternal life?

01:19.815 --> 01:21.818
He said to him, what is written in the law?

01:22.178 --> 01:22.819
How do you read it?

01:23.560 --> 01:32.112
And he answered, you shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength and with all your mind and your neighbor as yourself.

01:33.033 --> 01:33.874
And he said to him,

01:34.210 --> 01:37.093
You have answered correctly, do this and you will live."

01:38.415 --> 01:41.519
But he, desiring to justify himself, said to Jesus.

01:42.259 --> 01:43.321
And who is my neighbor?

01:44.182 --> 01:53.032
Jesus replied, a man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho and he fell among robbers who stripped him and beat him and departed, leaving him half dead.

01:53.893 --> 01:56.356
Now by chance, a priest was walking down that road.

01:56.717 --> 01:58.939
And when he saw him, he passed by on the other side.

01:59.760 --> 02:01.362
So likewise, a Levite

02:01.442 --> 02:04.766
when he came to the place and saw him, passed by on the other side.

02:05.466 --> 02:08.610
But a Samaritan, as he journeyed, came to where he was.

02:08.630 --> 02:11.193
And when he saw him, he had compassion.

02:12.034 --> 02:15.878
He went to him and bound up his wounds, pouring on oil and wine.

02:16.599 --> 02:20.523
Then he set him on his own animal and brought him to an inn and took care of him.

02:21.384 --> 02:26.770
And the next day he took out to Daenerai and gave them to the innkeeper saying, take care of him.

02:27.151 --> 02:30.194
And whatever more you spend, I will repay you when I come back.

02:31.202 --> 02:35.969
Which of these three do you think proved to be a neighbor to the man who fell among the robbers?

02:36.529 --> 02:38.893
He said, the one who showed him mercy.

02:39.493 --> 02:43.599
And Jesus said to him, you go and do likewise.

02:44.520 --> 02:45.362
This is God's word.

02:45.882 --> 02:46.543
Let's pray together.

02:48.606 --> 02:54.013
God, we thank you for your word and how your word reveals your character and your heart.

02:55.215 --> 02:57.338
And God, we need that more than ever right now.

02:57.759 --> 03:00.242
In a time when people are crying out,

03:00.546 --> 03:01.948
and not sure where to look.

03:02.529 --> 03:06.194
God, we look to you and we thank you that you have spoken.

03:06.234 --> 03:09.119
Your voice has broken the silence.

03:09.259 --> 03:10.381
You have pursued us.

03:10.421 --> 03:11.883
You have initiated with us.

03:12.784 --> 03:18.573
And so God, we pray that your word would give us guidance and clarity and purpose in this time, Lord.

03:19.274 --> 03:22.118
Thank you, Lord, that your spirit is at work amongst us.

03:22.619 --> 03:30.290
And as your word is proclaimed today, we pray that your spirit would be working at hearts and in homes and in communities

03:30.370 --> 03:34.559
All over the city today, we pray this in Jesus name, amen.

03:37.867 --> 03:42.738
Well, right now our culture is really being driven by self-preservation.

03:43.138 --> 03:51.932
That's what you see when you try to go to the grocery store and everyone's lining up and people are fighting over toilet paper and everyone's stocking up on everything.

03:52.312 --> 03:54.095
We're driven by self-preservation.

03:54.155 --> 04:01.467
Even many of the good measures that people are taking to be safe, it's ultimately for the safety of self.

04:02.168 --> 04:05.353
But here's what I want you to hear today loud and clear.

04:05.994 --> 04:11.122
For followers of Jesus, what's greater than self-preservation is love.

04:11.682 --> 04:15.166
And love is self-giving and sacrificial.

04:16.007 --> 04:19.071
And listen, I'm not saying that self-preservation is a bad thing.

04:19.212 --> 04:21.054
No, of course, you need to care for yourself.

04:21.094 --> 04:22.316
You need to take care of yourself.

04:22.356 --> 04:25.540
You need to be wise, especially right now.

04:26.140 --> 04:31.808
But while self-preservation is a value, what I'm saying for Christians is that love is a greater value.

04:32.308 --> 04:33.890
It's a greater priority for us.

04:33.950 --> 04:37.975
And not only is it a priority, it's a calling from God Himself.

04:38.897 --> 04:40.018
Think about it like this.

04:40.162 --> 04:46.032
with everything with the coronavirus, I certainly have a lot of worries and fears about everything that's going around.

04:46.132 --> 04:50.719
But honestly, I'm not that concerned for my own health in the midst of that.

04:51.420 --> 04:56.328
If what the medical professionals is true, then it's not that risky for me.

04:56.669 --> 05:01.577
At my age, and I don't have any preexisting conditions, I could probably get over it pretty quickly.

05:02.458 --> 05:07.346
But love calls me to not just look out for my own needs, but to the needs of others.

05:07.650 --> 05:16.726
So while I'm not too worried about getting the coronavirus, love makes me think of the fact that, well, if I get the coronavirus, then what about people in my church?

05:17.207 --> 05:17.988
What about neighbors?

05:18.569 --> 05:20.813
What about friends that I have?

05:20.833 --> 05:23.678
What about family who might be more vulnerable?

05:24.159 --> 05:30.770
Love calls me not just to self-preservation, but to giving of self for the good of others.

05:30.850 --> 05:34.676
That's what we need to be a people of love in this culture right now.

05:34.716 --> 05:37.640
And so to do that, we need to look to the scriptures.

05:37.800 --> 05:48.256
And so in this story in Luke chapter 10, it says that Jesus tells this lawyer that he needs to love the Lord and to love his neighbor.

05:49.057 --> 05:53.284
And the man then responds to Jesus and says, well, then who is my neighbor?

05:54.065 --> 05:57.490
And Jesus answers that question by telling this story.

05:57.634 --> 05:59.196
A man's walking down the street.

05:59.297 --> 06:01.881
Imagine it's Sunset Boulevard, maybe Gower.

06:02.602 --> 06:04.184
And all of a sudden he gets jumped.

06:04.825 --> 06:09.753
It says that he's robbed, he's beaten, and he's left on the side of the road half dead.

06:10.635 --> 06:12.458
And so this man's laying on the side of the road.

06:12.478 --> 06:13.920
He can't help himself.

06:14.861 --> 06:16.805
And it says that a priest walks by.

06:16.825 --> 06:20.230
A very prominent religious man.

06:20.971 --> 06:22.393
But maybe he was too busy.

06:22.454 --> 06:25.298
He just keeps going, ignores the man.

06:25.602 --> 06:27.665
And then another person comes by, it's a Levite.

06:27.745 --> 06:30.729
Again, it would have been another important religious person.

06:30.770 --> 06:31.410
And what does he do?

06:31.430 --> 06:32.752
He keeps going.

06:33.534 --> 06:36.578
He wouldn't associate with that type or he didn't have time to stop.

06:36.598 --> 06:38.941
Whatever the reason was, he doesn't stop.

06:39.502 --> 06:43.248
But then we are told that a Samaritan comes.

06:43.768 --> 06:47.634
And the Samaritan sees the man and has compassion.

06:48.034 --> 06:56.623
And his compassion leads him to going and caring for this man and binding up his wounds, taking him to an inn, actually giving his own money.

06:56.703 --> 07:03.230
He gives him open tab to the innkeeper saying, I'll pay whatever I need to later, just make sure to take care of this man.

07:03.990 --> 07:06.313
It's an incredible story that Jesus tells us.

07:06.753 --> 07:11.238
And it answers three of the most important questions that we get ever asked about love.

07:11.698 --> 07:13.740
And the first one is this, who is my neighbor?

07:14.761 --> 07:15.282
Now,

07:15.554 --> 07:31.921
What I want you to understand in this passage is that when it talks about love of neighbor, and Jesus speaks of this elsewhere, hear the man, the lawyer talking to Jesus mentions this, when it's talking about love of neighbor, this is a reference back to Leviticus 19.

07:32.141 --> 07:34.124
Everybody's favorite book of the Bible, Leviticus.

07:34.184 --> 07:42.578
Maybe you got to Leviticus 16 in like a year of plan and then stopped, but in Leviticus 19, it talks about love of neighbor.

07:42.914 --> 07:45.798
And the question there is, who's the neighbor?

07:45.878 --> 07:55.412
And if you go back in your Bibles and read in Leviticus 19, you'll see specifically that it's talking about the poor, the sojourners, the deaf, the blind.

07:56.233 --> 08:02.322
When it's talking about loving your neighbors in Leviticus 19, it's talking about the most vulnerable people.

08:03.223 --> 08:08.270
So you come to Luke 10 and Jesus tells this story and he's answering the question, who is my neighbor?

08:08.831 --> 08:11.154
Well, clearly it's someone who's vulnerable.

08:11.554 --> 08:15.498
But I think the answer gives us an even more practical question.

08:15.538 --> 08:18.862
Our neighbor is anyone who is in need.

08:20.043 --> 08:23.287
Whoever you come across that is in need, that is your neighbor.

08:23.347 --> 08:27.571
That is one that you are called by God to love and to show the love of God.

08:28.352 --> 08:34.058
And I love then how after Jesus tells this story, he flips the question on the man in a sense.

08:34.599 --> 08:37.842
The man had asked, who is my neighbor?

08:38.082 --> 08:44.572
And then Jesus tells the story and he asked the question, which of these three do you think proved to be a neighbor to the man?

08:45.573 --> 08:52.303
So while we're saying, well, I need to find someone who needs my help, he's saying, what kind of neighbor are you?

08:53.184 --> 08:55.087
He puts the onus on the man.

08:55.248 --> 09:00.876
And so I think for us, that's a way of getting us to the question of who are we?

09:01.036 --> 09:01.938
What's our character?

09:02.198 --> 09:07.666
How is the Lord shaping us and then using us in our society in a time like this?

09:08.002 --> 09:21.140
And so if our neighbors then are not just the person who's got the address, you know, that's a number up from yours or lives in the apartment next to you, our neighbor is, are those who are vulnerable and those who are in need.

09:21.400 --> 09:25.266
So let me ask you this, who around you is vulnerable right now?

09:25.987 --> 09:27.629
And what does it look like for you to love them?

09:28.410 --> 09:29.131
Who are the sick?

09:29.872 --> 09:31.474
Who are the elderly in your life?

09:31.810 --> 09:38.798
Who do you know that has pre-existing conditions that maybe is afraid right now, maybe is scared and maybe is isolated because of that?

09:39.619 --> 09:41.020
I think about my neighbor, Mary.

09:41.661 --> 09:42.522
She's in her 80s.

09:43.102 --> 09:44.584
She has a lot of health conditions.

09:45.085 --> 09:46.826
She can't go to the grocery store on her own.

09:47.507 --> 09:57.578
So I read the story and I think she's literally my physical neighbor, but she's the neighbor that I'm called to, especially in light of this coronavirus, where she's vulnerable.

09:58.339 --> 10:01.042
God has called me to pray for her and to help her

10:01.186 --> 10:06.355
If I'm going to go to the grocery store to get something from my family, I need to check in with Mary and say, what do you need?

10:06.435 --> 10:08.698
Let me bring you back something from the grocery store.

10:09.660 --> 10:10.722
So that's the first question.

10:11.523 --> 10:12.284
Who is my neighbor?

10:12.425 --> 10:13.246
It's the vulnerable.

10:13.707 --> 10:15.329
It's anyone who is in need.

10:15.890 --> 10:20.738
Second, the second question that we have to ask of this passage is, how do I show love?

10:21.700 --> 10:24.504
And you have a model of this from the Samaritan.

10:24.565 --> 10:27.890
And what we learn first is that love is compassionate.

10:28.610 --> 10:36.603
That's the first thing that it tells us about the Samaritan is that he had compassion on the man who was bleeding on the side of the road.

10:37.143 --> 10:38.706
Everyone else walked past him.

10:39.747 --> 10:45.036
The Samaritan looked at him and he saw the dignity in the man before he saw his needs.

10:45.677 --> 10:48.762
He recognized that he's a fellow brother.

10:48.862 --> 10:52.227
He's a human being made in the image of God.

10:52.748 --> 10:54.130
And so he had compassion on him.

10:54.594 --> 10:58.618
That word compassion literally means to suffer with.

10:59.599 --> 11:03.924
He cared enough to enter into this man's suffering.

11:04.805 --> 11:06.927
He didn't just look at him and feel bad.

11:06.967 --> 11:11.913
No, he had a compassion that compelled him to go and do something about it.

11:11.973 --> 11:14.576
So first of all, love is compassionate.

11:14.656 --> 11:17.639
Secondly, what we learn from this is that love is costly.

11:18.240 --> 11:20.342
I mean, literally in the story, it's costly.

11:20.382 --> 11:24.146
The Samaritan goes and has to pay money for the man to be

11:24.290 --> 11:25.091
taken care of.

11:26.113 --> 11:29.417
But I don't just mean, of course, that it's costly financially.

11:29.978 --> 11:34.504
In giving of his money, the man was showing that love is giving of self.

11:35.546 --> 11:42.415
That really is what love is in its essence to be able to sacrifice.

11:43.517 --> 11:50.747
Love is having a commitment to the good of another person that you are willing to sacrifice your own good for their benefit.

11:51.668 --> 11:52.850
Love is sacrificial.

11:52.994 --> 11:56.139
You can do something kind to someone, but not sacrifice.

11:56.559 --> 12:05.332
You could do something good to someone, maybe expecting something in return, but to love someone is actually to sacrifice for their well-being.

12:05.532 --> 12:09.798
So love is compassionate, love is costly.

12:09.818 --> 12:13.503
And then what we also see from this story is that love crosses boundaries.

12:14.445 --> 12:20.914
You've got to understand that in the first century, the Samaritans were considered enemies of the Jewish people.

12:21.282 --> 12:24.065
Samaritans were people who stayed back during the exile.

12:24.406 --> 12:26.528
They intermarried with other ethnicities.

12:26.588 --> 12:31.834
And so the Jews came back and they saw them as the worst of the worst.

12:31.874 --> 12:33.176
They wouldn't want to go near them.

12:33.216 --> 12:38.983
If they needed to go through a Samaritan town instead they would go around it.

12:39.383 --> 12:42.307
They looked down on the Samaritans so much.

12:43.288 --> 12:48.594
And yet Jesus tells this story or the hero of the story is a Samaritan.

12:49.346 --> 12:53.891
a man who's willing to cross boundaries because of love.

12:54.732 --> 13:03.341
And so when we think about the essence of love, this is so important because in our culture, the word gets love, the word love gets thrown around, of course, in so many different ways.

13:03.381 --> 13:07.385
And it becomes cheapened, it becomes shallow, it becomes sentimental.

13:07.866 --> 13:10.488
But scripture reminds us that love is sacrificial.

13:11.009 --> 13:15.794
That's the way that God has loved us and it's the way that God calls us to love others.

13:16.322 --> 13:17.844
So how does this apply for us today?

13:17.904 --> 13:23.633
Well, in the midst of the coronavirus and everything that's going on around it, God calls us to be people of love.

13:24.575 --> 13:33.368
I read an article earlier this week that was really helpful just in processing and thinking through everything that's going on in all the different opinions.

13:33.408 --> 13:37.234
It was by Andy Crouch, who's an article called Love and the Time of Coronavirus.

13:37.795 --> 13:38.936
And here's what he had to say.

13:39.798 --> 13:45.266
We need to redirect social energy from anxiety and panic to love and preparation.

13:46.082 --> 13:53.111
This crisis presents an extraordinary opportunity to fortify small communities of love and care for our neighbors.

13:54.052 --> 14:03.544
That will only happen if we lead in a way that reduces fear, increases faith, and re-oreans all of us from self-protection to serving others.

14:04.846 --> 14:14.578
That's what we can be, small communities of love that are reducing fear, increasing faith for the good of the city that the Lord has called us to.

14:15.074 --> 14:16.475
This is what the early church did.

14:16.515 --> 14:19.539
And this is one of the ways that the early church grew.

14:19.579 --> 14:27.327
In the first century, the Roman world, the Greco-Roman world, was there were commonly plagues.

14:28.207 --> 14:32.612
People were ridden with sickness and illness all the time.

14:33.313 --> 14:42.482
And what would happen is a plague would come and people would often leave the cities to stay away from the plague until people died out and then they would come back.

14:43.106 --> 14:56.441
But Christians actually had a reputation in the first couple of centuries that they were the ones who would stick around in the midst of a plague and care for those who were sick and wounded and who other people didn't want to get near.

14:57.482 --> 14:58.523
And why would they do this?

14:59.244 --> 15:02.648
Because they were following Jesus, the very one who would touch the leper.

15:03.689 --> 15:07.954
And so we see how the love of God compels us

15:08.034 --> 15:09.476
We see that in the scriptures.

15:09.817 --> 15:11.339
You see that in the early church.

15:11.699 --> 15:14.884
And that's what God is calling us to, to be a people of love.

15:15.605 --> 15:17.227
And there's a lot of ways that we can love.

15:17.287 --> 15:18.829
We can pray for our neighbors.

15:18.890 --> 15:20.151
We can encourage our neighbors.

15:20.171 --> 15:22.094
We can help them out practically.

15:22.114 --> 15:30.386
Right now with so many limitations, it's easy to focus on limitations and to be able to think, well, what can I do?

15:30.722 --> 15:35.870
I'm not even supposed to be around people or I'm not even, all these things that I'm a part of have been canceled.

15:36.191 --> 15:37.974
What can I actually do to help?

15:38.775 --> 15:44.004
What I want to encourage you to do in the midst of this is don't focus on your limitations.

15:44.444 --> 15:46.928
Get creative and find ways to show love.

15:47.529 --> 15:57.906
If you can't be face to face with people that you care about in the midst of this, go out of your way to reach out to them via text message or email or FaceTime, whatever that is.

15:58.050 --> 16:04.960
If you're not in your regular work environments or whatever that is, get creative, pray, ask the Lord.

16:05.601 --> 16:09.246
Don't allow this thing to leave you paralyzed thinking, what can I do?

16:10.188 --> 16:13.353
God can do anything and He's called you into that work.

16:13.453 --> 16:17.218
He wants to be at work in His people during this time.

16:17.939 --> 16:19.982
So we've asked the question, who is my neighbor?

16:20.022 --> 16:21.985
And then how do I show love?

16:22.566 --> 16:27.954
But the third question is really important and it's this, where does this kind of love come from?

16:28.930 --> 16:31.573
And to answer this question, I want you to think about this.

16:31.873 --> 16:36.659
In the story of the Good Samaritan, who do you identify with?

16:36.679 --> 16:42.726
Some of you might identify with the priest or the Levite.

16:42.786 --> 16:57.042
In fact, that's probably the common person that we identify with in the story that, well, I'm busy and so I see a need, but I have something else to do or I think I'm important or I don't want to cross kind of these ethnic boundaries, whatever that is.

16:57.282 --> 17:03.027
We often identify with one of those characters in the story.

17:03.067 --> 17:20.003
But when we zoom out from Luke 10 and look at the scriptures as a whole, I think that what we see is that we're not ultimately the person in the story who's either ignoring the person or even the Samaritan who goes and helps the person.

17:20.063 --> 17:27.250
We identify with the person who's on the side of the road, helpless, who can't get himself up.

17:28.162 --> 17:31.308
who needs someone to come and rescue him.

17:31.328 --> 17:41.908
The scriptures say that not only is that the case, but that it's not just because we were mistreating or robbed, that we actually chose to be in that situation.

17:41.948 --> 17:48.079
And the good Samaritan here in this story is pointing us ultimately to Christ.

17:48.099 --> 17:51.826
I mean, Jesus is telling this story, but he's telling it on the way to the cross.

17:52.194 --> 17:57.940
And the good Samaritan is pointing to what Christ accomplishes and what He does through the cross.

17:58.660 --> 18:00.562
There we are laying on the side of the road.

18:01.023 --> 18:01.983
And He comes.

18:02.864 --> 18:05.407
He looks upon you with compassion.

18:05.467 --> 18:08.029
He goes to you.

18:08.049 --> 18:10.772
He binds up your wounds.

18:11.132 --> 18:12.293
He cares for you.

18:12.333 --> 18:15.917
He gives of Himself for you.

18:15.957 --> 18:17.458
And that is love.

18:17.759 --> 18:21.202
Greater love knows no one than this.

18:21.378 --> 18:24.483
that he laid down his life for his friends.

18:25.184 --> 18:31.794
And so when we talk about this story, it ultimately points us to the love of God in Christ.

18:32.435 --> 18:43.973
And that's the good news of the gospel, that Christ died for us, that while we were still sinners, he died for us and God demonstrates his love in that very way.

18:44.894 --> 18:50.162
So I want to remind you today of the good news of Christ's death on the cross for your sins.

18:51.074 --> 18:55.941
I want to remind you that you were loved by God, that God cares for you.

18:56.001 --> 18:57.783
He binds up your wounds.

18:58.204 --> 18:59.105
He carries you.

18:59.165 --> 19:01.308
He has given of himself.

19:01.388 --> 19:04.913
He has shown sacrificial love for you.

19:04.973 --> 19:09.019
And we receive that through faith, through trusting in him.

19:09.079 --> 19:14.706
But remember that this love that God gives us in Christ, it doesn't stop with us.

19:14.726 --> 19:20.274
1 John 4 19 says, we love because he first loved

19:20.482 --> 19:20.802
us.

19:21.744 --> 19:25.249
Now 2 Corinthians 5 says that Christ love compels us.

19:25.970 --> 19:32.039
So God's love comes to us, but then it goes through us to those who are around us.

19:32.900 --> 19:40.531
And so while I want to call you to be a people of love and to go out in love, what you've got to understand first and foremost is that you are loved.

19:41.372 --> 19:47.922
And as you are filled with God's love, that will be the very way that you love others.

19:48.482 --> 19:53.987
You know, the coronavirus has everyone talking about life and death.

19:54.868 --> 20:01.634
And it's certainly a time as we hear the death toll rise and we hear about the fear of sickness.

20:02.335 --> 20:10.283
It is certainly a time where we need to be aware of the brevity and fragility of life that our days are numbered.

20:10.923 --> 20:18.130
And as Christians, that's something that we don't have to be afraid of to live as Christ and to die as gain.

20:18.594 --> 20:25.522
So listen, we need to be cautious, we need to be careful, we need to be wise, but we do not need to be afraid.

20:26.263 --> 20:30.488
What we have in Christ cannot be taken from us.

20:31.410 --> 20:37.337
Romans 8 talks about how nothing can separate us from the love of God.

20:37.897 --> 20:48.210
Nothing, not the coronavirus, not cancer, not sickness, not illness, nothing can separate us from the love of God.

20:48.450 --> 20:59.425
So right now, with everything that's going on, I hope that you can be rooted in God's love and that you can know that you can have a peace that surpasses understanding.

21:01.047 --> 21:07.456
Earlier this week, I was talking to my mother-in-law and she was telling me about her neighbor.

21:08.057 --> 21:14.706
And her neighbor, Barb, is a woman that every time we go back to my in-laws house in Indiana,

21:14.882 --> 21:16.585
We see Barb at least once.

21:16.665 --> 21:21.813
She usually comes over and takes a family picture of all of us, and she's the sweetest lady.

21:22.354 --> 21:24.577
She's just kind and sweet.

21:24.717 --> 21:30.486
She was married for 60 years, and Barb was nearing the end of her life.

21:30.767 --> 21:31.728
She had gotten sick.

21:31.868 --> 21:43.346
She'd been in hospice for a while, and my father-in-law and my mother-in-law went to be with her, and they sat around her bed, and they sang hymns.

21:43.682 --> 21:45.885
And they sang him after him after him.

21:45.905 --> 21:49.670
And during one hymn, they sang over and over again of the love of Jesus.

21:50.631 --> 21:52.814
And she heard of the love of Jesus.

21:52.894 --> 21:57.661
And literally the name Jesus was the last thing that she heard.

21:58.082 --> 22:00.285
And then she breathed her last breath.

22:01.346 --> 22:02.808
And I reflected on that.

22:03.028 --> 22:13.202
And I was so saddened to hear of her loss and yet so encouraged to think that she passed to be with the Lord surrounded by friends.

22:13.602 --> 22:18.610
hearing the love of Jesus and knowing that she is deeply loved by Him.

22:19.591 --> 22:25.059
Now, we can have that same experience today or whenever that day comes for us.

22:25.700 --> 22:34.894
So I want to remind you of God's love for you and to keep focused on His love during this time and to be an instrument of His love.

22:35.415 --> 22:39.361
There are so many needs around us, but God's love is abundant.

22:39.481 --> 22:42.546
His mercy is overflowing in our lives.

22:42.786 --> 22:43.527
Let's pray together.

22:46.010 --> 22:52.038
God, we thank you for your unfailing, steadfast love.

22:53.380 --> 23:08.421
And Lord, we pray that we would know that while we have sinned, while we find ourselves in a situation where we are helpless, we are powerless to change ourselves, that you have sent your Son Christ to come and rescue us.

23:09.242 --> 23:12.466
We thank you that Jesus looks upon us with compassion

23:12.802 --> 23:15.725
that he heals our wounds, that he brings us together.

23:16.846 --> 23:25.394
And God, we pray that as we receive love from you, that in this time, in this city, that you would use us as instruments of your love.

23:26.295 --> 23:33.743
God, give us wisdom in knowing how to engage with all of this and what to go to and what to be a part of and where to step back.

23:34.443 --> 23:37.286
But Lord, also give us courage to love boldly.

23:38.247 --> 23:41.330
Remind us to pray, show us where the needs are,

23:41.890 --> 23:44.144
And Lord, help us to keep our eyes fixed on you.

23:44.667 --> 23:45.955
We pray this in Jesus' name.

23:46.679 --> 23:47.122
Amen.

